<section class="card">
  <h2>About Kale</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Cold-tolerant greens with one of the widest frost buffers in the garden.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Kale is highly frost-tolerant and can handle multiple light freezes.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), kale is rarely limited by first frost. Instead, viability is determined by whether your season provides enough time and moderate heat for steady leaf production.
  </p>

  <p>
    Kale is one of the most reliable short-season crops because it tolerates cool soil, light frost, and gradual fall cooling. In most climates, frost extends harvest rather than ending it.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start indoors:</strong> 4–6 weeks before transplant window (optional)</li>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 2–4 weeks before to 2 weeks after last frost</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 45–75 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Hardy (handles multiple frosts)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Kale is forgiving, but growth speed still depends on temperature and seasonal heat.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Cold Tolerance & Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–75°F (13–24°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~40°F (4°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> Above ~85°F (29°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Kale commonly tolerates light frost and may improve in flavor after cool nights. While 32°F (0°C) marks the frost boundary for planning consistency, kale often continues producing below that threshold until sustained hard freezes occur.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For a deeper explanation of light vs hard freezes, see:
    <a href="/guides/light-freeze-vs-hard-freeze/">Light freeze vs hard freeze</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring vs Fall Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Kale performs well in both spring and fall:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring crop:</strong> Early sowing into workable soil; steady growth through cool weeks.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall crop:</strong> Count backward from first frost and allow buffer for slower late-season growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a> to anchor fall sowing from your frost boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~600–1,000 GDD (base 50) for steady leaf production</p>

  <p>
    Kale is not highly heat-demanding, but accumulated seasonal heat influences how quickly leaves reach harvest size.
    In cooler summers, maturity may extend beyond labeled days-to-maturity.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For how frost boundaries and heat budgets work together, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Many kale varieties begin harvest in <strong>45–75 frost-free days</strong>.
    Because kale tolerates frost, the true limitation in short seasons is often growth rate, not survival.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (one of the most reliable options)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Rarely; early varieties fit comfortably</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Usually no; frost tolerance provides natural buffer</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Kale tolerates light frost and often continues growing after first frost at 32°F (0°C).
    Sustained hard freezes eventually halt growth, but first frost is not an immediate harvest cutoff.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose early varieties for tighter frost windows</li>
    <li>Sow early in spring for maximum runway</li>
    <li>For fall crops, allow buffer for slower growth as days shorten</li>
    <li>Use full sun exposure to preserve effective heat accumulation</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, kale is viable in most short seasons because its frost tolerance provides margin.
    The main constraint becomes growth rate and heat accumulation rather than survival at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can kale survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Kale commonly tolerates light frost and can withstand multiple cool nights before sustained hard freezing halts growth.
  </p>

  <h3>Is kale good for very short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Its modest heat requirement and frost tolerance make it one of the safest crops for short growing windows.
  </p>

  <h3>Does frost improve kale flavor?</h3>
  <p>
    Many growers report improved sweetness after cool nights, though this varies by variety and conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) frost timing as the planning boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Kale tolerates frost and often extends harvest beyond first frost.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 45–75 days, ~600–1,000 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>